April 3, 2009

Dear Governor Perdue,

Like many other environmental educators in our state, I too am shocked at your recommendation to dismantle North Carolina’s Office of Environmental Education.  Obviously, early in your tenure, you realized some of the problems that formal educators in our state face by reorganizing your Education advisors.  

I am a tenured professor of Education at UNCG.  I have served on the faculty at UNCG for nearly seventeen years. I came to UNCG and taught environmental education before we had an environmental education certification program in North Carolina. I have advocated tirelessly for the incorporation of this certification program into our state education certification program, as have many others, but to no avail. My students want this desperately. But, rather than moving forward toward that goal, you propose to move us backwards by dismantling the very office that has worked to achieve this end. I would suggest that instead of eliminating the Office of Environmental Education that you take some of your necessary budget cuts from the Department of Public Instruction (DPI).  The savings would be immense, not paltry.

If we destroy our environment, and we are making good progress in that direction, then we will not need education. As Henry David Thoreau said, “What is the use of a house if you haven't got a tolerable planet to put it on?”

DPI is an excellent example of a place where you could make the kind of budget cut that you propose for the Office of Environmental Education and minimally affect services. Additionally, you risk alienating fewer teachers, professors and informal educators who believe that the most important education we can offer at this time is environmental education.

I just read in our University newspaper, Campus Weekly, that you will be giving the commencement address at UNCG on May 15, 2009. I hope that you will seriously reconsider your suggestion to eliminate the Office of Environmental Education.  I think that you will get a much more enthusiastic reception in May from our many students and faculty if you take a strong stand to support this vital component of becoming a learned person.  

Sincerely.

Dr. Catherine E. Matthews
Professor, CUI, Science Education
UNCG

