My name is Leigh Anne Shore.  I am a teacher and have some concerns about how teachers are sometimes treated in the field of education.



To give you some background, I am 31 years old and have been teaching for 8 years.  I went to UNC-CH and graduated with 2 majors and the equivalent of a minor.  (BA K-6 Elementary Education, BA English, and Minor in ESL.)  As a result I have 2 teaching licenses K-6 Elementary Ed and K-12 ESL.  I have always wanted to be a teacher.  When I moved from regular Ed to ESL, I decided that I needed more Spanish-Speaking skills, so I attended a prestigious language school in Middlebury, Vermont, where I became relatively proficient in conversational Spanish.  Then I applied for a scholarship to study abroad for 3 months to further my Spanish-speaking skills.  I did this of my own volition and paid for it out of my own pocket.  Finally, in 2007, I got my National Board Certification at an ESL specialist.  I am only telling you all of this, so that you know I am dedicated to the profession as well as my students, and I have worked very hard to be the very best teacher I can be. 



Here are my issues:



1) The state paid for my National Board Certification.  I was pregnant while I worked on it, and had an infant when I took the test.  That was my choice.  The plan all along was that I would work part time once our baby boy was born, and then go back to teaching full time as he reached school age.  I was unaware until I was well into the process that I had to teach FULL TIME in order to not refund the state the $2500 fee.  I knew that I had to teach in NC the year following my certification, and I planned for that, but it wasn't until I was 6 months pregnant and nearly through the process that a friend told me that I would have to work FULL TIME.  Although the website, may have been changed by now, it was not even mentioned there.  I read all of the criteria BEFORE I signed on for the process.



Now, I am being asked to refund the state $2500 dollars.  I appealed in a letter, but received what I believe to be a form letter in return denying my request.  (It did not address any of the points in my appeal.)  I am currently teaching ESL, as a specialist, part time, and I did so last year,so I AM using what I learned from the National Board Process in NC.  Isn't that the whole point of the rule about teaching in NC the year following the process?  I plan to continue to teach in NC in the coming years.  However, I have to say that I am now disheartened.



Would you please consider taking a look at this case.  I have taught for 2 years part time following the NBC process which is equivalent to 1 year teaching.  At the very least, could you please use what power you have to reduce the cost and require me to pay only 1/2 of the fee back since I am working 1/2 time?  Although I do not feel that I should have to repay the $2500 fee, these two options seem more fair and legitimate to me.



2) I have become disheartened by this whole situation.  You see, I have taught ESL for 6 years now.  (I taught regular ed before.)  During those 6 years I did not work with another ESL teacher who was licensed in that area until this year.  They came in lateral entry or with another teaching degree and did far less work to get their ESL license than I did, if they got it at all.  They also were sometimes paid more than me, based on years of experience in education or years with the state.  These things have always seemed unfair to me.  I often feel punished for going to school to become a teacher instead of coming in to teaching from a different profession. 



I have done the best I can to be the best teacher I can be.  PLEASE consider taking a look at this case for me.  Call me if you have any questions (336.945.4295), or respond to this email. 



Thank you for your time.



Leigh Anne Thomasson Shore

